I truly cannot even begin to describe the impact this had on me. Having members of my family struggle in the past with this terrible disease it's the hardest thing in the world to go through and to see someone you love suffering. It is so amazing to see what you guys are doing and it is so inspiring. This tremendously, well executed documentary means the world to me and helped me so much with some emotions that I was struggling to face too. Even though I don't know y'all I am so deeply proud of the both of you and will continue to support you through your journeys. To see the two of you put yourselves out there on such a deep level and use your platform for good, always since the beginning means everything. For you guys to share the statics that are not at all talked about with cancer, just Thank You for educating people on how this has such a huge impact on peoples lives. I respect the shit out of you guys and I know for a fact Sean is a looking down on the two of you so proud of his sons and the men you guys are becoming. May God continue to bless the both of you and your family and may your father Rest in Paradise.
With love, Gabrielle

snippet.textDisplay: I definitely feel your pain, my grandpa is my father figure and definitely the strongest person I know. He dealt with so many treatments from cancer, many operations, losing more than half his weight in less than 5 months. It was hard for him to go through all that and be in the hospital for months not being to eat whole foods. Especially when they operated him and found that the cancer had spread. Every night one of our family members, including myself, spent the night with him to watch over and make sure he didn't choke on the tube he had down his throat. It didn't  matter that I had school in the morning or my mom had to be at work by 8 a.m. It fucking broke my heart seeing my grandma cry every night as I lied next to her, also to see my mom break down and I had to console her. My mom alongside my grandpa are the strongest people in my life and to see her react that way has left a permanent pinch in my heart I won't ever forget the feeling of. Even now as I'm typing this tears are brought to my eyes. I hope nobody goes through this kind of pain and sadness because it's one of the worst feelings that won't ever settle within. It's been 2 years already and even though I try to bury the feeling, I can't.

snippet.textDisplay:
I lost my grandma one and a half year ago and I know exactly how you guys feel. She was my best friend as well. I struggled with showing my emotions. I pushed all the bad feelings away and tried to be happy all the time, the problem was that I didn't want somebody to see me cry because I thought, that because of me everyone else would get sad as well. Meanwhile I figured how to express my emotions and that I can share them with my family and friends. Especially with my family because they of course feel the same way. I thought "staying strong" for them is the way to go but at the end I realised that it's easier to show them how I feel so they can help me the way I tried to help them.
